{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17492894","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17492894"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:49:10+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:49:10+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1181"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1181","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1181"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.13,0.04,0.62,0.1,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1181"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90843"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1181","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1181"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1181"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74906"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"247"},{"type":"tags","id":"377"},{"type":"tags","id":"3884"},{"type":"tags","id":"8228"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12468"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31144"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90843","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/90843"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 70-year-old woman presents to her General Practice clinic with a self-detected left breast lump. She has a medical history of asthma which is well-controlled. Her only regular medication is a steroid inhaler. She is otherwise in good health. On examination, there is a 2 cm firm, irregular mass in the upper outer quadrant of her left breast. There is no skin tethering or nipple retraction. No lymphadenopathy is palpable.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA mammogram shows a 15 mm stellate lesion corresponding to the palpable mass. Ultrasound of the breast confirms the mammographic findings and axillary ultrasound is normal. A core biopsy of the breast lesion confirms a grade 2 infiltrating ductal carcinoma which is ER/PR positive and HER2 negative. Staging scans show no metastastic disease.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate treatment?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Primary hormone therapy","Excisional biopsy","Wide local excision and sentinel node biopsy","Neoadjuvant chemotherapy","Mastectomy and sentinel node biopsy"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has a small (15 mm), node-negative breast cancer. She is otherwise in good health with no contraindications to surgery. Therefore, the most appropriate management is \u003Cstrong\u003Ewide local excision and sentinel node biopsy\u003C/strong\u003E. This allows the tumour to be completely excised with clear margins, while minimising the extent of surgery. Sentinel node biopsy is indicated for staging, as she has no clinical evidence of nodal involvement. Adjuvant radiotherapy and endocrine therapy would likely be recommended postoperatively.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrimary hormone therapy\u003C/strong\u003E (e.g. with an aromatase inhibitor such as letrozole) may be considered in elderly patients with ER-positive tumours who are unfit for or decline surgery. However, this patient is fit for surgery, so this would not be first-line treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eexcisional biopsy\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated, as the diagnosis has already been confirmed by core biopsy. Excisional biopsy would be considered if the core biopsy was inconclusive.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENeoadjuvant chemotherapy\u003C/strong\u003E may be used to downstage large or locally advanced tumours prior to surgery. However, this patient has a small tumour which is suitable for primary surgical management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Emastectomy\u003C/strong\u003E is more extensive surgery than is required for a small tumour. Mastectomy would be considered for larger tumours, multifocal disease, or if the tumour size is large relative to the breast size. This patient has a 15 mm tumour so breast-conserving surgery is feasible.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Wide local excision and sentinel node biopsy is the most appropriate treatment for a small, node-negative breast cancer in an elderly patient with no contraindications to surgery.","Primary endocrine therapy may be considered in elderly patients with ER-positive tumours who are unfit for or decline surgery.","Neoadjuvant chemotherapy may be used to downstage large or locally advanced tumours prior to surgery."],"references":["Heilat G, Brennan M, French J. Update on the management of early-stage breast cancer. Australian Journal for General Practitioners. 2019;48:604-8. Available at: https://www1.racgp.org.au/ajgp/2019/september/management-of-early-stage-breast-cancer"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74906"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1181"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74906","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/74906"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-14T17:46:05+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-14T17:46:05+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1181"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90843"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21